              <b>What is a prediction market?</b>
            </button>
          </h2>
        </div>

        <div id="collapseOne" class="collapse" aria-labelledby="headingOne" data-parent="#faq">
          <div class="card-body">
            A prediction market is a market comprised of contracts which represent presently unknown future outcomes that traders can buy and sell based on their beliefs of the probability of the outcome occuring. A prediction market contract trades between $0.00 and $1.00 and is binary in the sense that it will either pay out $0.00 because it did not happen or $1.00 because it did happen. For example, a contract might be currently priced at $0.30 per share. If you, a trader, think the outcome is very likely to occur, you might purchase the contract because it pays out $1.00 if it occurs but only currently costs $0.30.
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="card">
        <div class="card-header" id="headingTwo">
          <h2 class="mb-0">
            <button class="btn btn-link collapsed" type="button" data-toggle="collapse" data-target="#collapseTwo" aria-expanded="false" aria-controls="collapseTwo" style="color: black">
              <b>What is the difference between Clubs, Seasons, and Markets and why do they all exist?</b>
            </button>
          </h2>
        </div>
        <div id="collapseTwo" class="collapse" aria-labelledby="headingTwo" data-parent="#faq">
          <div class="card-body">
            <u>In short</u>
            <br>
            A Club has many Seasons and a Season has many Markets.
            <br>
            <br>
            <u>In long</u>
            <br>
            A <i>Club</i> is the highest level and is meant to organize you and your friends into groups. For example, if you use Predicts Hit with your college friends and your coworkers, you might have a Club for your college friends and a Club for your coworkers.
            <br>
            <br>
            A <i>Season</i> is the middle level, is contained within a Club, and tracks how users perform over multiple markets. For example, if you wanted to predict outcomes for a video game tourament, you might create a season for that tournament and invite users from your Club who are interested in that tournament. Users would start with some set amount of money, as determined by the Season creator, and they would use those funds to predict the outcomes of multiple markets. Whoever has the most money at the end of the Season wins! 
            <br>
            <br>
            A <i>Market</i> is the lowest level and is contained within a Season. For the same video game example, you might create multiple markets to predict how well certain teams or players perform. Users in the Season would predict the outcomes for these markets using their Season funds and try to correctly guess the outcomes.
            <br>
            <br>
            <u>An example</u>
            <br>
            I want to use Predicts Hit with my coworkers so I create a Club called 'Big Business' and invite all of my coworkers who want to play. Some of my coworkers want to predict the outcomes of the US Open tennis tournament and some of my coworkers want to predict the outcome of the next season of the Bachelor. Therefore I create a Season called 'US Open 2021' and another Season called 'The Bachelor Season 25' and invite whoever wants to participate from my Club Big Business into each Season. Then, for example, for my Season Us Open 2021, I might create multiple markets for events throughout the tournament. For example, I might create markets that track tournament-long outcomes such as 'Who will win the tournament?' or 'Who will serve the most aces?' or 'Will Federer smash a racquet during the tournament?' I might also create game specific markets such as 'Who will win in the match between Player X and Player Y' or 'how many sets will be played in the match between Player X and Player Y?' Be creative -- as long as there is a discrete, knowable outcome, you can make a market for it! For The Bachelor Seaosn 25 I might make markets each week to predict who will receive roses or who will the Bachelor kiss, etc. Then, at the end of the US Open or the Bachelor Season, we would see who performed best over all of the markets throughout the Season.
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
