      <div class="card">
        <div class="card-header" id="headingFive">
          <h2 class="mb-0">
            <button class="btn btn-link collapsed" type="button" data-toggle="collapse" data-target="#collapseFive" aria-expanded="false" aria-controls="collapseFive" style="color: black">
              <b>The price says it is $0.XX but when I purchase multiple contracts the price goes up...what gives?</b>
            </button>
          </h2>
        </div>
        <div id="collapseFive" class="collapse" aria-labelledby="headingFive" data-parent="#faq">
          <div class="card-body">
            This is a result of the algorithm that is being used to calculate the price. The price initially shown for each contract is assuming you only are buying 1 contract. The more contracts you buy simultanouesly, the more you increase the demand for the contract, thus translating to a higher price as a result of the algorithm described above. So it's not that the price of the first contract is increasing, it's just that each incremental contract you want to buy might come at a higher cost than originally posted. This is similar to how standard markets work where only a certain number of shares might be posted at the asking price and if you want to buy more than that number of shares you will have to pay more for those additional shares.
          </div>
        </div>
